* The original planned release date for this film was November 3, 2017, but when Marvel announced plans for ''[[Spider-Man: Homecoming]]'', it was pushed back to November 2, 2018 and ''[[Thor: Ragnarok]]'' took its original release date. It later got postponed again to its current release date to make way for ''[[Ant-Man and the Wasp (film)|Ant-Man and the Wasp]]''.{{cite|ref=true|url=http://marvel.com/news/movies/23549/captain_marvel_soars_into_the_marvel_cinematic_universe|title=Captain Marvel Soars Into the Marvel Cinematic Universe|work=Marvel|first=Marc|last=Strom|date=28 October 2014|accessdate=10 February 2015}}{{cite|ref=true|url=http://marvel.com/news/movies/24065/marvel_studios_schedules_new_release_dates_for_4_films|title=Marvel Studios Schedules New Release Dates for 4 Films|work=Marvel|first=Marc|last=Strom|date=9 February 2015|accessdate=10 May 2015}}{{cite|ref=true|url=http://marvel.com/news/movies/25244/marvel_studios_phase_3_update|title=Marvel Studios Phase 3 Update|last=Strom|first=Marc|work=Marvel.com|date=8 October 2015|accessdate=8 October 2015}}
* Location shooting for this film took place in January 2018;{{cite|ref=true|url= http://www.vulture.com/2018/02/kevin-feige-on-okoye-captain-marvel-and-michelle-pfeiffer.html|title= Kevin Feige on the Future of Marvel’s Women (Including Danai, Tessa, Brie, and Michelle)|work= Vulture|last= Buchanan|first= Kyle|date= 16 February 2018|accessdate= 27 February 2018}}}} while principal photography started on March 19, 2018,{{r|{{cite web|url= https://screenrant.com/captain-marvel-set-video-start-filming/|title= Captain Marvel Set Video Confirms Start Of Filming|work= Screen Rant|last= Hood|first= Cooper|date= March 19 2018|accessdate= March 20 2018}} and wrapped on July 6, 2018.{{cite|ref=true|url= https://www.instagram.com/p/Bk6RJaTH9R3/|title= We got next...|work= Instagram|last= Fleck|first= Ryan|date= July 6, 2018|accessdate= July 7, 2018|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20180824105538/https://www.instagram.com/p/Bk6RJaTH9R3/|archivedate= August 24, 2018}}
* Before she was eventually replaced by Lashana Lynch, {{WP|DeWanda Wise}} was originally cast as Maria Rambeau, but later had to exit due to scheduling conflicts.{{cite|ref=true|refname=DeWanda Wise|url= http://deadline.com/2018/01/shes-gotta-have-it-dewanda-wise-captain-marvel-brie-larson-1202235891/|title= ‘She’s Gotta Have It’ Star DeWanda Wise Lands Plum Role Opposite Brie Larson In ‘Captain Marvel’|work= Deadline|last= Fleming|first= Mike Jr.|date= 4 January 2018|accessdate= 5 January 2018}}{{cite|ref=true|url= http://deadline.com/2018/03/dewanda-wise-captain-marvel-exit-scheduling-conflict-shes-gotta-have-it-1202338916/|title= DeWanda Wise Exits ‘Captain Marvel’ Role|work= Deadline|last= Hipes|first= Patrick|date= March 15, 2018|accessdate= March 16, 2018}}
* With a worldwide total box office gross of $1.128 billion, this film became the 5th-highest-grossing film of 2019,{{cite|ref=true|url= https://www.boxofficemojo.com/year/world/2019/|title= 2019 Worldwide Box Office|work= Box Office Mojo|accessdate= January 5, 2020}} and at its peak the 22nd-highest-grossing film of all time.{{cite|ref=true|url= https://www.boxofficemojo.com/alltime/world/|title= All Time Box Office|accessdate= January 5, 2020|work= Box Office Mojo|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20190615102541/https://www.boxofficemojo.com/alltime/world/|archivedate=June 15, 2019}}
| Trivia                  = * Early drafts of the film included the character of [[Helen Cobb (Earth-616)|Helen Cobb]].{{cite|ref=true|url=https://comicbook.com/marvel/2019/03/04/captain-marvel-character-helen-cobb-comics-mar-vell/|title='Captain Marvel' Originally Included Key Marvel Comics Character|work=ComicBook.com|first=Brandon|last=Davis|date=4 March 2019|accessdate=8 March 2019}}
* Filmmaker {{WP|James Cameron}}'s '90s action movies served as inspiration for the tone of ''Captain Marvel''. Co-director [[Ryan Fleck]] cites ''{{Wc|terminator|Terminator 2|Terminator 2}}'' as a specific reference point.{{cite|ref=true|refname=EO|url=https://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/captain-marvel-15-spoiler-facts-directors-anna-boden-ryan-fleck/|title=Captain Marvel: 15 Spoiler Facts From Directors Anna Boden And Ryan Fleck|work=Empire Online|first=Ben|last=Travis|date=11 March 2019|accessdate=22 March 2019}}
* Earlier visions of the film were structured differently. They were told in a more linear fashion and started with Carol Danvers' life on Earth and friendship with [[Maria Rambeau (Earth-199999)|Maria Rambeau]].<ref name="EO"/>
* Before deciding to have {{WP|Annette Bening}} portray the incarnation of the [[Supreme Intelligence (Earth-199999)|Supreme Intelligence]] that Danvers sees when she communes with it, by means of having the Supreme Intelligence assume the appearance of the person an individual feels more comfortable with, a separate figure was going to be the Supreme Intelligence.<ref name="EO"/>
* The 2004 romantic film ''{{WP|Eternal Sunshine Of The Spotless Mind}}'' was one of the inspirations for a sequence directors Anna Boden and Ryan Fleck call the "Mind-frak;" the scene in which [[Talos (Earth-199999)|Talos]] trawls through Carol's muddled memories.<ref name="EO"/>
* When Carol crash-lands into the Blockbuster Video store, she is startled and blasts a ''{{WP|True Lies}}'' cardboard standee. Boden and Fleck's original idea that was not signed off was to have the standee be for ''{{WP|The Mask (film)|The Mask}}'', and to have Carol mistake the titular character's green head for a [[Deviant Skrulls|Skrull]].<ref name="EO"/>
* The mid-credits scene featuring the [[Avengers (Earth-199999)|Avengers]] was directed by ''[[Avengers: Endgame]]'' directors [[Anthony Russo|Anthony]] and [[Joseph Russo|Joe Russo]].<ref name="EO"/>
* A scrapped idea for the post-credits scene was going to have [[Yon-Rogg (Earth-199999)|Yon-Rogg]]'s pod crash-land on [[Sakaar]].<ref name="EO"/>
* The film includes several tributes to Stephen "Cajun" Del Bagno, an Air Force Major who consulted on the movie. He died in a jet crash in April 2018, a week after concluding his work on the film. The most prominent of these tributes is a {{WP|Piano burning|burning piano}}, a traditional send-off ceremony for fallen fighter pilots, which appears for a few frames when Talos is probing Carol's memories. Del Bagno is mentioned several times in the credit roll, and the filmmakers reportedly snuck his callsign into the background of several scenes. He also has a brief cameo, playing a game of pool with Carol in a quick flashback.{{cite|ref=true|url=http://airshowstuff.com/v4/2019/did-you-notice-the-burning-piano-in-captain-marvel-heres-the-special-meaning-behind-it-and-its-connection-to-a-real-life-hero/|title=Did You Notice The Burning Piano In Captain Marvel? Here’s The Special Meaning Behind It – And Its Connection To A Real Life Hero|work=AirShowStuff|date=12 March 2019|accessdate=23 June 2019}}
* The Marvel logo shown before the movies starts features a tribute to [[Stan Lee]], who died a few months before the film's release.
